iculate beginning of Hegel's Logic, "Being, pure Being," identical with "Nothing," and argues that the Logic serves as an especially appropriate tool for understanding the sudden violent action that strikes Claggart dead. Through these and other readings, Nuzzo finds a fresh way to address interpretive issues that have remained unresolved for almost two centuries in Hegel scholarship, and also presents well-known works of literature in an entirely new light. This account of Hegel's Logic is framed by the need for an interpretive tool able to orient our understanding of the contemporary world as mired in an unprecedented global crisis. How can the story of our historical present—the tragedy or the comedy we all play parts in—be told? What is the inner logic of our changing world?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 0aLogic. 4aPhilosophy : Critical Theory. 4aPhilosophy : German Idealism. 4aPhilosophy : Hegel. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Literature. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438472065423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438472065/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles